    "Statement": "There are infinitely many primes with last digit 7.",
    "Proof": "Assume for contradiction that there are only finitely many primes ending with the digit 7, denoted as p1, p2, ..., pn. Construct a new number P = 10*p1*p2*...*pn - 3, which also ends with the digit 7. If P is prime, this contradicts our initial assumption. If P is not prime, it must be divisible by some prime number. However, P leaves a remainder of 3 when divided by any of p1, p2, ..., pn, so it must be divisible by a prime not in our original list and ending with 7, again contradicting our initial assumption. Therefore, there must be infinitely many primes ending with 7."
