"Theorem 1": "There are infinitely many prime numbers with the last digit 7.",
"Proof 1": "Assume for contradiction that there are only finitely many primes with the last digit 7, denoted as p1, p2, ..., pn. Construct a number P such that P equals 10 times the product of these primes plus 7. The number P also ends in 7. If P is prime, it contradicts the assumption as it is not in our list. If P is not prime, it cannot be divided by any prime ending in 1, 3, or 9 because P leaves a remainder of 7 when divided by 10. Moreover, it cannot be divided by any prime ending in 7 because it leaves a remainder of 7 when divided by any of the primes p1, p2, ..., pn. Thus, P must be prime, which contradicts the assumption again. Therefore, there are infinitely many primes with the last digit 7."
